<paragraph blockId="6.[189,646,1393,1419]" box="[189,646,1393,1419]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,646,1393,1419]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,646,1393,1419]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Distribution, ecology, and phenology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1399,1439,1500]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName box="[189,533,1439,1465]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="longipedunculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,533,1439,1465]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Euphorbia longipedunculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[547,644,1440,1466]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
grows in open cerrado vegetation (ʻcampo limpoʼ) near the Chapada dos Veadeiros in northern 
<collectingRegion box="[606,677,1474,1500]" country="Brazil" name="Goias" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Goiás</collectingRegion>
, within the Cerrado domain (
<figureCitation box="[1021,1093,1474,1500]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[207,1386,650,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-108@4.[189,1398,632,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Geographical distribution ofEuphorbia blepharadena O.L.M.Silva &amp; Cordeiro sp. nov. (triangle), E. longipedunculata O.L.M.Silva &amp; Riina sp. nov. (star) and E. sobolifera O.L.M.Silva &amp; P.J.Braun sp. nov. (square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5706228" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5706228/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="78" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="6.[189,578,1538,1565]" box="[189,578,1538,1565]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,578,1538,1565]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,578,1538,1565]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Provisional conservation status</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[188,1400,1585,1717]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">
<taxonomicName box="[189,526,1585,1611]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Euphorbia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="longipedunculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,526,1585,1611]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Euphorbia longipedunculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[532,621,1585,1611]" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is only known from a single location (
<figureCitation box="[1068,1139,1585,1611]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[207,1386,650,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-108@4.[189,1398,632,1890]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Geographical distribution ofEuphorbia blepharadena O.L.M.Silva &amp; Cordeiro sp. nov. (triangle), E. longipedunculata O.L.M.Silva &amp; Riina sp. nov. (star) and E. sobolifera O.L.M.Silva &amp; P.J.Braun sp. nov. (square)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5706228" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5706228/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), it has AOO &lt;
<quantity box="[1316,1389,1585,1613]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" unit="km" value="10.0">10 km</quantity>
² and EOO &lt;
<quantity box="[331,424,1619,1648]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="78" unit="km" value="100.0">100 km</quantity>
². As this location is close to roadsides, it is subject to continuing decline in area, extent and quality due to the always growing anthropic pressure in Central 
<collectingCountry box="[1061,1136,1654,1680]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="78">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. In the light of this, we suggest that this new species be classified as Critically Endangered (CR; B2ab[iii]).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
